# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: benzocaine
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:benzocaine/1-10-phenanthroline] Abbreviated "phen", or sometimes "o-phen" for ortho-phenanthroline, it is used as a ligand in coordination chemistry, forming strong complexes with most metal ions.
[src:benzocaine/1-10-phenanthroline] Phenanthroline can be prepared by two successive Skraup reactions of glycerol with *o*-phenylenediamine, catalyzed by sulfuric acid, and an oxidizing agent, traditionally aqueous arsenic acid or nitrobenzene.
[src:benzocaine/1-10-phenanthroline] Dehydration of glycerol gives acrolein which condenses with the amine followed by a cyclization.
[src:benzocaine/1-10-phenanthroline] Oxidation of 1,10-phenanthroline with a mixture of nitric and sulfuric acids gives 1,10-phenanthroline-5,6-dione.
[src:benzocaine/1-10-phenanthroline] 1,10-Phenanthroline forms many coordination complexes.
[src:benzocaine/1-10-phenanthroline] One example is the iron complex called ferroin.
[src:benzocaine/1-10-phenanthroline] Alkyllithium reagents form deeply colored derivatives with phenanthroline.
[src:benzocaine/1-10-phenanthroline] The alkyllithium content of solutions can be determined by treatment of such reagents with small amounts of phenanthroline (ca.
[src:benzocaine/1-10-phenanthroline] 1 mg) followed by titration with alcohols to a colourless endpoint.
[src:benzocaine/1-10-phenanthroline] Grignard reagents may be similarly titrated.
[src:benzocaine/1-10-phenanthroline] Phenanthroline is used in biochemical and pharmacological research as an inhibitor of the deubiquitination enzyme Rpn11.
[src:benzocaine/12-o-tetradecanoylphorbol-13-acetate] In ROS biology, superoxide was identified as the major reactive oxygen species induced by TPA/PMA but not by ionomycin in mouse macrophages.
[src:benzocaine/12-o-tetradecanoylphorbol-13-acetate] Thus, TPA/PMA has been routinely used as an inducer for endogenous superoxide production.
[src:benzocaine/12-o-tetradecanoylphorbol-13-acetate] TPA has a specific use in cancer diagnostics as a B-cell specific mitogen in cytogenetic testing.
[src:benzocaine/12-o-tetradecanoylphorbol-13-acetate] Cells must be divided in a cytogenic test to view the chromosomes.
[src:benzocaine/12-o-tetradecanoylphorbol-13-acetate] TPA is used to stimulate division of B-cells during cytogenetic diagnosis of B-cell cancers such as chronic lymphocytic leukemia.
[src:benzocaine/12-o-tetradecanoylphorbol-13-acetate] TPA is also commonly used together with ionomycin to stimulate T-cell activation, proliferation, and cytokine production, and is used in protocols for intracellular staining of these cytokines.
[src:benzocaine/12-o-tetradecanoylphorbol-13-acetate] TPA induces KSHV reactivation in PEL cell cultures via stimulation of the mitogen-activated protein kinase (MAPK)/extracellular signal-regulated kinase (ERK) pathway.
[src:benzocaine/12-o-tetradecanoylphorbol-13-acetate] The pathway involves the activation of the early-immediate viral protein RTA that contributes to the activation of the lytic cycle.
[src:benzocaine/12-o-tetradecanoylphorbol-13-acetate] TPA was first found in the Croton plant, a shrub found in Southeast Asia, exposure to which provokes a poison ivy-like rash.
[src:benzocaine/3-4-diaminopyridine] As of January 2017, Catalyst and another US company, Jacobus Pharmaceutical, which had been manufacturing and giving it away for free since the 1990s, were both seeking FDA approval for their iterations and marketing rights.
[src:benzocaine/3-4-diaminopyridine] Amifampridine phosphate (Firdapse) has orphan drug status in the EU for Lambert–Eaton myasthenic syndrome and Catalyst holds both an orphan designation and a breakthrough therapy designation in the US.
[src:benzocaine/3-4-diaminopyridine] In May 2019, the US Food and Drug Administration (FDA) approved amifampridine tablets under the brand name **Ruzurgi** for the treatment of Lambert-Eaton myasthenic syndrome (LEMS) in people 6 to less than 17 years of age.
[src:benzocaine/3-4-diaminopyridine] Ruzurgi is no longer available in the United States.
[src:benzocaine/3-4-diaminopyridine] As of November 2018, the only other treatment approved by the FDA for LEMS (Firdapse) was only approved for use in adults.
[src:benzocaine/3-4-diaminopyridine] In 2022, Firdapse approval was expanded to include pediatric patients 6 years of age or older.
[src:benzocaine/3-4-diaminopyridine] In 2024, the FDA approved a supplemental New Drug Application increasing the maximum daily dose of Firdapse (amifampridine) for adults and pediatric patients weighing more than 45 kg from 80 mg to 100 mg.
[src:benzocaine/3-4-diaminopyridine] Amifampridine is used to treat many of the congenital myasthenic syndromes, particularly those with defects in choline acetyltransferase, downstream kinase 7, and those where any kind of defect causes "fast channel" behaviour of the acetylcholine receptor.
[src:benzocaine/3-4-diaminopyridine] It is also used to treat symptoms of Lambert–Eaton myasthenic syndrome.
[src:benzocaine/3-4-diaminopyridine] Because it affects voltage-gated ion channels in the heart, it is contraindicated in people with long QT syndrome and in people taking a drug that might prolong QT time like sultopride, disopyramide, cisapride, domperidone, rifampicin or ketoconazol.
[src:benzocaine/3-4-diaminopyridine] It is also contraindicated in people with epilepsy or badly controlled asthma.
[src:benzocaine/3-4-diaminopyridine] The dose-limiting side effects include tingling or numbness, difficulty sleeping, fatigue, and loss of muscle strength.
[src:benzocaine/3-4-diaminopyridine] Seizures have been observed in patients without a history of seizures.
[src:benzocaine/3-4-diaminopyridine] The combination of amifampridine with pharmaceuticals that prolong QT time increases the risk of ventricular tachycardia, especially torsade de pointes; and combination with drugs that lower the seizure threshold increases the risk of seizures.
[src:benzocaine/3-4-diaminopyridine] Interactions via the liver's cytochrome P450 enzyme system are considered unlikely.
[src:benzocaine/3-4-diaminopyridine] In Lambert–Eaton myasthenic syndrome, acetylcholine release is inhibited as antibodies involved in the host response against certain cancers cross-react with Ca2+ channels on the prejunctional membrane.
[src:benzocaine/3-4-diaminopyridine] Amifampridine works by blocking potassium channel efflux in nerve terminals so that action potential duration is increased.
[src:benzocaine/3-4-diaminopyridine] Ca2+ channels can then be open for a longer time and allow greater acetylcholine release to stimulate muscle at the end plate.
[src:benzocaine/3-4-diaminopyridine] Amifampridine is quickly and almost completely (93–100%) absorbed from the gut.
[src:benzocaine/3-4-diaminopyridine] In a study with 91 healthy subjects, maximum amifampridine concentrations in blood plasma were reached after 0.6 (±0.25) hours when taken without food, or after 1.3 (±0.9) hours after a fatty meal, meaning that the speed of absorption varies widely.
[src:benzocaine/3-4-diaminopyridine] Biological half-life (2.5±0.7 hrs) and the area under the curve (AUC = 117±77 ng∙h/ml) also vary widely between subjects, but are nearly independent of food intake.
[src:benzocaine/3-4-diaminopyridine] The substance is deactivated by acetylation via N-acetyltransferases to the single metabolite 3-*N*-acetylamifampridine.
[src:benzocaine/3-4-diaminopyridine] Activity of these enzymes (primarily N-acetyltransferase 2) in different individuals seems to be primarily responsible for the mentioned differences in half-life and AUC: the latter is increased up to 9-fold in slow metabolizers as compared to fast metabolizers.
[src:benzocaine/3-4-diaminopyridine] Amifampridine is eliminated via the kidneys and urine to 74–81% as *N*-acetylamifampridine and to 19% in unchanged form.
[src:benzocaine/3-4-diaminopyridine] 3,4-Diaminopyridine is yellow solid, although commercial samples often appear brownish.
[src:benzocaine/3-4-diaminopyridine] It is readily soluble in alcohols and hot water, but only slightly in diethyl ether.
[src:benzocaine/3-4-diaminopyridine] Solubility in water at 20 °C (68 °F) is 25 g/L.
[src:benzocaine/3-4-diaminopyridine] The drug formulation amifampridine phosphate contains the phosphate salt, more specifically 4-aminopyridine-3-ylammonium dihydrogen phosphate.
[src:benzocaine/3-4-diaminopyridine] This salt forms prismatic, monoclinic crystals (space group C2/c) and is readily soluble in water.
[src:benzocaine/3-4-diaminopyridine] The phosphate salt is stable, and does not require refrigeration.
[src:benzocaine/3-4-diaminopyridine] The development of amifampridine and its phosphate has brought attention to orphan drug policies that grant market exclusivity as an incentive for companies to develop therapies for conditions that affect small numbers of people.
[src:benzocaine/3-4-diaminopyridine] Amifampridine, also called 3,4-DAP, was discovered in Scotland in the 1970s, and doctors in Sweden first showed its use in LEMS in the 1980s.
[src:benzocaine/3-4-diaminopyridine] In the 1990s, doctors in the US, on behalf of Muscular Dystrophy Association, approached a small family-owned manufacturer of active pharmaceutical ingredients in New Jersey, Jacobus Pharmaceuticals, about manufacturing amifampridine so they could test it in clinical trials.
[src:benzocaine/3-4-diaminopyridine] Jacobus elected to give the drug away to this subset of LEMS patients, and did so for about twenty years.
[src:benzocaine/3-4-diaminopyridine] Doctors at the Assistance Publique – Hôpitaux de Paris had created a phosphate salt of 3,4-DAP (3,4-DAPP), and obtained an orphan designation for it in Europe in 2002.
[src:benzocaine/3-4-diaminopyridine] The hospital licensed the intellectual property on the phosphate form to the French biopharma company OPI, which was acquired by EUSA Pharma in 2007, and the orphan application was transferred to EUSA in 2008.
[src:benzocaine/3-4-diaminopyridine] In 2008 EUSA submitted an application for approval to market the phosphate form to the European Medicines Agency under the brand name Zenas.
[src:benzocaine/3-4-diaminopyridine] EUSA, through a vehicle called Huxley Pharmaceuticals, sold the rights to 3,4-DAPP to BioMarin in 2009, the same year that 3,4-DAPP was approved in Europe under the new name Firdapse.
[src:benzocaine/3-4-diaminopyridine] The licensing of Firdapse in 2010 in Europe led to a sharp increase in price for the drug.
[src:benzocaine/3-4-diaminopyridine] In some cases, this has led to hospitals using an unlicensed form rather than the licensed agent, as the price difference proved prohibitive.
[src:benzocaine/3-4-diaminopyridine] BioMarin has been criticized for licensing the drug on the basis of previously conducted research, and yet charging exorbitantly for it.
[src:benzocaine/3-4-diaminopyridine] A group of UK neurologists and pediatricians petitioned to prime minister David Cameron in an open letter to review the situation.
[src:benzocaine/3-4-diaminopyridine] Meanwhile, in Europe, a task force of neurologists had recommended 3,4-DAP as the firstline treatment for LEMS symptoms in 2006, even though there was no approved form for marketing; it was being supplied *ad hoc*.
[src:benzocaine/3-4-diaminopyridine] In 2007 the drug's international nonproprietary name was published by the WHO.
[src:benzocaine/3-4-diaminopyridine] In October 2012, while BioMarin had a Phase III trial ongoing in the US, it licensed the US rights to 3,4-DAPP, including the orphan designation and the ongoing trial, to Catalyst Pharmaceuticals.
[src:benzocaine/3-4-diaminopyridine] Catalyst anticipated that it could earn $300 to $900 million per year in sales at peak sales for treatment of people with LEMS and other indications, and analysts anticipated the drug would be priced at around. $100,000 in the US.
[src:benzocaine/3-4-diaminopyridine] Catalyst went on to obtain a breakthrough therapy designation for 3,4-DAPP in LEMS in 2013, an orphan designation for congenital myasthenic syndromes in 2015 and an orphan designation for myasthenia gravis in 2016.
[src:benzocaine/3-4-diaminopyridine] In August 2013, analysts anticipated that FDA approval would be granted to Catalyst in LEMS by 2015.
[src:benzocaine/3-4-diaminopyridine] In October 2014, Catalyst began making available under an expanded access program.
[src:benzocaine/3-4-diaminopyridine] In March 2015, Catalyst obtained an orphan designation for the use of 3,4-DAPP to treat of congenital myasthenic syndrome.
[src:benzocaine/3-4-diaminopyridine] In April 2015, Jacobus presented clinical trial results with 3,4-DAP at a scientific meeting.
[src:benzocaine/3-4-diaminopyridine] In December 2015, Catalyst submitted its new drug application to the FDA, and in February 2016 the FDA refused to accept it, on the basis that it wasn't complete.
[src:benzocaine/3-4-diaminopyridine] In April 2016 the FDA told Catalyst it would have to gather further data.
[src:benzocaine/3-4-diaminopyridine] Catalyst cut 30% of its workforce, mainly from the commercial team it was building to support an approved product, to save money to conduct the trials.
[src:benzocaine/3-4-diaminopyridine] In March 2018 the company re-submitted its NDA.
[src:benzocaine/3-4-diaminopyridine] The FDA approved amifampridine for the treatment of adults with Lambert-Eaton myasthenic syndrome on November 29, 2018.
[src:benzocaine/3-4-diaminopyridine] In February 2019, US Senator Bernie Sanders questioned the high price ($375,000) charged by Catalyst Pharmaceuticals for Firdapse.
[src:benzocaine/3-4-diaminopyridine] In May 2019, the privately held US company Jacobus Pharmaceutical, Princeton, New Jersey gained approval by the FDA for amifampridine tablets (*Ruzurgi*) for the treatment of LEMS in patients 6 to less than 17 years of age.
[src:benzocaine/3-4-diaminopyridine] This is the first FDA approval of a treatment specifically for pediatric patients with LEMS.
[src:benzocaine/3-4-diaminopyridine] *Firdapse* is only approved for use in adults.
[src:benzocaine/3-4-diaminopyridine] Although *Ruzurgi* has been approved for pediatric patients, this approval makes it possible for adults with LEMS to get the drug off-label.
[src:benzocaine/3-4-diaminopyridine] Jacobus Pharmaceutical had been manufacturing and giving it away for free since the 1990s.
[src:benzocaine/3-4-diaminopyridine] The FDA decision dropped the stock of Catalyst Pharmaceuticals.
[src:benzocaine/3-4-diaminopyridine] The company's stock price has dropped about 50%.
[src:benzocaine/3-4-diaminopyridine] On January 28, 2022, in Catalyst Pharmaceuticals, Inc. v.
[src:benzocaine/3-4-diaminopyridine] Becerra, the Eleventh Circuit upheld orphan exclusivity for Catalyst Pharmaceuticals and its drug Firdapse.
[src:benzocaine/3-4-diaminopyridine] With this decision, the Eleventh Circuit rejected the FDA's interpretation of orphan exclusivity and concluded that the agency had improperly approved a competitor product from Jacobus Pharmaceutical.
[src:benzocaine/3-4-diaminopyridine] In October 2022, Firdapse approval was expanded to include pediatric patients 6 years of age or older.
[src:benzocaine/3-4-diaminopyridine] In May 2024, the FDA approved a supplemental New Drug Application increasing the indicated maximum daily dose of Firdapse (amifampridine) for adults and pediatric patients weighing more than 45 kg from 80 mg to 100 mg.
[src:benzocaine/3-4-diaminopyridine] Amifampridine has also been proposed for the treatment of multiple sclerosis (MS).
[src:benzocaine/3-4-diaminopyridine] A 2002 Cochrane systematic review found that there was no unbiased data to support its use for treating MS.
[src:benzocaine/3-4-diaminopyridine] Isomazole is a drug that is made from an amifampridine precursor.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminobenzoic-acid] Food sources of PABA include liver, brewer's yeast (and unfiltered beer), kidney, molasses, mushrooms, and whole grains.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminobenzoic-acid] Other food sources of PABA include spinach and oat seeds.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminobenzoic-acid] PABA is an intermediate in the synthesis of folate by bacteria, plants, and fungi.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminobenzoic-acid] Many bacteria, including those found in the human intestinal tract such as *E. coli*, generate PABA from chorismate by the combined action of the enzymes 4-amino-4-deoxychorismate synthase and 4-amino-4-deoxychorismate lyase.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminobenzoic-acid] Plants produce PABA in their chloroplasts, and store it as a glucose ester (*p*ABA-Glc) in their tissues.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminobenzoic-acid] The malarial protozoan *Plasmodium* only make PABA when necessary, preferring to get it from the surroundings if able to.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminobenzoic-acid] Some bacteria, including a few found in the human microbiome, are unable to make PABA for themselves but can use PABA to make folate.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminobenzoic-acid] A few are very efficient at the PABA-to-folate conversion despite not making their own PABA.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminobenzoic-acid] Sulfonamide drugs are structurally similar to PABA, and their antibacterial activity is due to their ability to interfere with the conversion of PABA to folate by the enzyme dihydropteroate synthetase.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminobenzoic-acid] Thus, bacterial growth is limited through folate deficiency.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminobenzoic-acid] PABA has been referred to historically as "vitamin Bx", but plays no direct role in animal cells and is hence no longer recognized as a vitamin.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminobenzoic-acid] Animals (including humans) are unable to use PABA in any way and so require folate from dietary sources such as green leafy vegetables.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminobenzoic-acid] PABA can play a role in the supply of folate to an animal via its microbiome; this is best demonstrated in the worm *C. elegans*, in which addition of PABA could increase folate production by resident *E. coli* and correct for deficiencies.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminobenzoic-acid] The *C. elegans* folate transporter only works with the reduced form (tetrahydrofolate, THF and derivatives such as folinic acid), not regular folic acid.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminobenzoic-acid] Any folic acid from the environment is only usable following spontaneous breakdown to PABA-glu, which *E. coli* uses to make THF.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminobenzoic-acid] In contrast, humans can directly use oxidized folates thanks to the proton-coupled folate transporter and have no need for this detour; this "recycling" of PABA-glu would, at best, compensate for folate degredation.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminobenzoic-acid] The above do not seem to apply in normal mammals, however.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminobenzoic-acid] Despite detection of gut-produced folate being incorporated into mammals, *ex vivo* folate synthesis capacity of fecal bacteria have no correlation with the folate status of their donors.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminobenzoic-acid] Furthermore, comparison with germ-free animals show that under a chow diet, the mouse microbiome is a net consumer of folate.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminobenzoic-acid] The caveat is that the mouse chow is more folate-rich than typical human diets and may be encouraging a shift towards a folate-consuming microbiome.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminobenzoic-acid] There are no reports of any usefulness of PABA in germ-free animals.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminobenzoic-acid] PABA and its salts are used in nutritional epidemiological studies to assess the completeness of 24-hour urine collection for the determination of urinary sodium, potassium, or nitrogen levels.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminobenzoic-acid] The potassium salt (potassium paraaminobenzoate, "aminobenzoate potassium") is used as a drug against fibrotic skin disorders, such as Peyronie's disease, under the brand name Potaba.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminobenzoic-acid] It is believed to work by inhibiting fibroblast glycosaminoglycan secretion and stabilizing monoamine oxidase A activity.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminobenzoic-acid] PABA is also occasionally used in pill form by sufferers of irritable bowel syndrome to treat its associated gastrointestinal symptoms.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminobenzoic-acid] PABA derivatives have also been proposed to function as acetylcholinesterase inhibitors in diseases that cause deficient cholinergic systems, such as Alzheimer's Disease.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminobenzoic-acid] Despite the lack of any recognized syndromes of PABA deficiency in humans, except for those who lack the colonic bacteria that generate PABA, many claims of benefit are made by commercial suppliers of PABA as a nutritional supplement.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminobenzoic-acid] The benefit is claimed for fatigue, irritability, depression, weeping eczema (moist eczema), scleroderma (premature hardening of the skin), patchy pigment loss in the skin (vitiligo), and premature grey hair.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminobenzoic-acid] PABA finds use in the biomedical sector.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminobenzoic-acid] Its derivatives are found as a structural component in 1.5% of a database of 12111 commercial drugs.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminobenzoic-acid] Other uses include its conversion to specialty azo dyes and crosslinking agents.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminobenzoic-acid] PABA is also used as a biodegradable pesticide, though its use is now limited due to evolution of new variants of bio-pesticides.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminobenzoic-acid] Specifically, studies have shown that PABA photodegrades through an O2-mediated pathway in which PABA is oxidized by O2 via hydrogen abstraction and decarboxylation.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminobenzoic-acid] In the past, PABA was widely used in sunscreens as a UV filter.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminobenzoic-acid] It is a UVB absorber, meaning it can absorb wavelengths between 290 and 320 nm. while still allowing UVA wavelengths between 320-400 nm to pass through, producing a tan.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminobenzoic-acid] The chemical structure of PABA, with the amino and carboxyl groups being *para* to each other, allows for easy electron delocalization, which reduces the gap between the highest occupied molecular orbital (HOMO) and lowest unoccupied molecular orbital (LUMO).
[src:benzocaine/4-aminobenzoic-acid] This makes it easier for the electrons in PABA to transition to a higher energy state upon absorbing light.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminobenzoic-acid] Patented in 1943, PABA was one of the first active ingredients to be used in sunscreen.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminobenzoic-acid] The first *in vivo* studies on mice showed that PABA reduced UV damage.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminobenzoic-acid] In addition, it was shown to protect against skin tumors in rodents, as shown by a 1975 study ran by Dr.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminobenzoic-acid] However, animal and *in vitro* studies in the early 1980s suggested PABA might increase the risk of cellular UV damage.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminobenzoic-acid] On the basis of these studies, as well as problems with allergies and clothing discoloration, PABA fell out of favor as a sunscreen.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminobenzoic-acid] In 2008 it was banned as a sunscreen ingredient in the European Union and in 2019 the FDA proposed its limited use.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminobenzoic-acid] However, water-insoluble PABA derivatives such as padimate O are currently used in some cosmetic products including mascara, concealer, and matte lipsticks.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminobenzoic-acid] As of 2008, the advancement of new sunscreen is focused on developing a broad spectrum of active ingredients that provide consistent protection across all wavelengths, including UVA.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminobenzoic-acid] Researchers are considering the PABA–TiO2 Hybrid Nanostructures that result from the method of aqueous in situ synthesis with PABA and TiO2.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminobenzoic-acid] PABA is largely nontoxic; the median lethal dose of PABA in dogs (oral) is 2 g/kg.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminobenzoic-acid] Allergic reactions, specifically allergic contact dermatitis and photocontact dermatitis, to PABA can occur.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminobenzoic-acid] It is formed in the metabolism of certain ester-type local anesthetics, and many allergic reactions to local anesthetics are the result of reactions to PABA.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminopyridine] In the laboratory, 4-AP is a useful pharmacological tool in studying various potassium conductances in physiology and biophysics.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminopyridine] It is a relatively selective blocker of members of Kv1 (Shaker, KCNA) family of voltage-activated K+ channels.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminopyridine] However, 4-AP has been shown to potentiate voltage-gated Ca2+ channel currents independent of effects on voltage-activated K+ channels.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminopyridine] 4-Aminopyridine is a potent convulsant and is used to generate seizures in animal models for the evaluation of antiseizure agents.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminopyridine] 4-Aminopyridine is also used under the trade name Avitrol as 0.5% or 1% in bird control bait.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminopyridine] It causes convulsions and, infrequently, death, depending on dosage.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminopyridine] The manufacturer says the proper dose should cause epileptic-like convulsions which cause the poisoned birds to emit distress calls resulting in the flock leaving the site; if the dose was sub-lethal, the birds will recover after 4 or more hours without long-term ill effect.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminopyridine] The amount of bait should be limited so that relatively few birds are poisoned, causing the remainder of the flock to be frightened away with a minimum of mortality.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminopyridine] A lethal dose will usually cause death within an hour.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminopyridine] The use of 4-aminopyridine in bird control has been criticized by the Humane Society of the United States.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminopyridine] Fampridine has been used clinically in Lambert–Eaton myasthenic syndrome and multiple sclerosis.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminopyridine] It acts by blocking voltage-gated potassium channels, prolonging action potentials and thereby increasing neurotransmitter release at the neuromuscular junction.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminopyridine] The drug has been shown to reverse saxitoxin and tetrodotoxin toxicity in tissue and animal experiments.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminopyridine] In calcium entry blocker overdose in humans, 4-aminopyridine can increase the cytosolic Ca2+ concentration very efficiently independent of the calcium channels.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminopyridine] Fampridine has been shown to improve visual function and motor skills and relieve fatigue in patients with multiple sclerosis (MS).
[src:benzocaine/4-aminopyridine] However, the effect of the drug is strongly established for walking capacity only.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminopyridine] Common side effects include dizziness, nervousness and nausea, and the incidence of adverse effects was shown to be less than 5% in all studies.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminopyridine] 4-AP works as a potassium channel blocker.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminopyridine] Strong potassium currents decrease action potential duration and amplitude, which increases the probability of conduction failure − a well documented characteristic of demyelinated axons.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminopyridine] Potassium channel blockade has the effect of increasing axonal action potential propagation and improving the probability of synaptic vesicle release.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminopyridine] A study has shown that 4-AP is a potent calcium channel activator and can improve synaptic and neuromuscular function by directly acting on the calcium channel beta subunit.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminopyridine] MS patients treated with 4-AP exhibited a response rate of 29.5% to 80%.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminopyridine] A long-term study (32 months) indicated that 80-90% of patients who initially responded to 4-AP exhibited long-term benefits.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminopyridine] Although improving symptoms, 4-AP does not inhibit progression of MS.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminopyridine] Another study, conducted in Brazil, showed that treatment based on fampridine was considered efficient in 70% of the patients.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminopyridine] Spinal cord injury patients have also seen improvement with 4-AP therapy.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminopyridine] These improvements include sensory, motor and pulmonary function, with a decrease in spasticity and pain.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminopyridine] 4-Aminopyridine is a gene-targeted therapy option for KCNA2-related disorders with a gain-of-function (GOF) or some mix-of-function (MOF) gene mutations.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminopyridine] It has shown to improve seizure control, gait, ataxia, alertness, and cognition.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminopyridine] GOF KCNA2 disorders are caused by voltage-gated potassium channels in the central nervous system that stay open and allow too much flow of potassium currents.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminopyridine] Some MOF KCNA2 disorders also act like GOF in regards to their flow of potassium through the channel which is why they may also benefit from 4-AP therapy.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminopyridine] 4-AP acts by closing these channels and improves the natural flow of potassium through the neuron.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminopyridine] As of 2025 the use of 4-AP for KCNA2 is in an experimental stage, but it has shown significant improvement for most patients that have used it.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminopyridine] Out of 13 documented patients, eight became seizure free, two others experienced a reduction in seizures, and 11 had improved gait, ataxia, alertness, cognition, or speech.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminopyridine] Only one patient experienced side effects of increased seizures and no other symptoms were reported.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminopyridine] Authors of the first 4-AP KCNA2 study created an online tool to guide physicians in identifying which KCNA2 patients would benefit from this therapy.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminopyridine] It is publicly accessible due to the importance for treating this disease from young age.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminopyridine] See the article for details on accessing this information.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminopyridine] Clinical studies have shown that 4-AP is capable of reversing the effects of tetrodotoxin poisoning in animals, however, its effectiveness as an antidote in humans has not yet been determined.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminopyridine] Case reports have shown that overdoses with 4-AP can lead to paresthesias, seizures, and atrial fibrillation.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminopyridine] 4-aminopyridine is excreted by the kidneys.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminopyridine] 4-AP should not be given to people with significant kidney disease (e.g., acute kidney injury or advanced chronic kidney disease) due to the higher risk of seizures with increased circulating levels of 4-AP.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminopyridine] The drug was originally intended, by Acorda Therapeutics, to have the brand name *Amaya*, however the name was changed to *Ampyra* to avoid potential confusion with other marketed pharmaceuticals.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminopyridine] Four of Acorda's patents pertaining to Ampyra were invalidated in 2017 by the United States District Court for the District of Delaware and a fifth patent expired in 2018.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminopyridine] Since then, generic alternatives have been developed for the U.S. market.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminopyridine] The drug is marketed by Biogen Idec in Canada as *Fampyra* and as *Dalstep* in India by Sun Pharma.
[src:benzocaine/4-aminopyridine] Dalfampridine completed Phase II clinical trials for Parkinson's disease in July 2014.
[src:benzocaine/benzocaine] It was first synthesised in 1890 in Germany and approved for medical use in 1902.
[src:benzocaine/benzocaine] Benzocaine is indicated to treat a variety of pain-related conditions.
[src:benzocaine/benzocaine] Benzocaine is generally well tolerated and non-toxic when applied topically as recommended.
[src:benzocaine/benzocaine] However, there have been reports of serious, life-threatening adverse effects (e.g., seizures, coma, irregular heart beat, respiratory depression) with over-application of topical products or when applying topical products that contain high concentrations of benzocaine to the skin.
[src:benzocaine/benzocaine] The topical use of higher concentration (10–20%) benzocaine products applied to the mouth or mucous membranes has been found to be a cause of methemoglobinemia, a disorder in which the amount of oxygen carried by the blood is greatly reduced.
[src:benzocaine/benzocaine] Benzocaine may cause allergic reactions.
[src:benzocaine/benzocaine] Benzocaine is the ethyl ester of *p*-aminobenzoic acid (PABA).
[src:benzocaine/benzocaine] It can be prepared from PABA and ethanol by Fischer esterification or via the reduction of ethyl *p*-nitrobenzoate.
[src:benzocaine/benzocaine] Benzocaine is sparingly soluble in water; it is more soluble in dilute acids and very soluble in ethanol, chloroform, and ethyl ether.
[src:benzocaine/benzocaine] The melting point of benzocaine is 88–92 °C, and the boiling point is about 310 °C.
[src:benzocaine/benzocaine] The density of benzocaine is 1.17 g/cm3.
[src:benzocaine/benzocaine] Benzocaine can be prepared by esterification using 4-aminobenzoic acid and ethanol.
[src:benzocaine/benzocaine] It can also be prepared by reduction of ethyl 4-nitrobenzoate to the amine.
[src:benzocaine/benzocaine] In industrial practice, the reducing agent is usually iron and water in the presence of a little acid.
[src:benzocaine/benzocaine] Benzocaine was first synthesized in 1890 by the German chemist Eduard Ritsert (1859–1946), in the town of Eberbach and introduced to the market in 1902 under the name "Anästhesin".
[src:benzocaine/benzocaine] Benzocaine is found, particularly in Britain, as an additive in street cocaine and also as a bulking agent in "legal highs".
[src:benzocaine/benzocaine] Benzocaine gives a numbing effect similar to cocaine and as a bulking and binding agent it can not be detected once mixed.
[src:benzocaine/benzocaine] It is the most popular cutting agent worldwide.
[src:benzocaine/benzocaine] Bath solutions of benzocaine and its derivatives are commonly used to anesthetize amphibians for surgery.
[src:benzocaine/benzocaine] Benzocaine-based anesthetics are potent and highly effective for both anesthesia and euthanasia in amphibians.
